  "response_text": "The trajectory of households engaged in social learning follows a sigmoid pattern characterized by rapid initial adoption, progressive deceleration, and eventual stabilization. At initialization (year 0), no households exhibit active social learning engagement. During the first two decades (years 0–21), the count increases steeply with a strongly positive trend, indicating rapid uptake of social learning behaviors among the population. This phase transitions around year 21 into a period of decelerating growth (years 22–40), where the rate of new adoption diminishes substantially, as indicated by reduced trend slopes. A change point at year 40 marks the transition to a plateau phase (years 40–63), during which the metric increases minimally until reaching an asymptote of approximately 32 households by year 63. From year 63 through the conclusion of the simulation at year 100, the count remains stable at roughly 32 households, representing a persistent subset of the total population that maintains social learning engagement. Across the full 100-year period, the average number of households engaged in social learning is approximately 27.4, with values ranging from the initial state of 0 to the maximum plateau of 32."  
}

